name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 12/ Fundamentally, $NFLX needs to change its strategy. Pulling back on original content output would be a good start. It might still struggle to compete in a world of escalating licensing costs, but it would at least create a path to financial viability

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 11/ Content output has done much to shift consumer perceptions of $NFLX's streaming platform, but the extreme cost of the effort does not appear to be paying off. The company continues to lose money at a worrying pace.

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 10/ Not all is lost, however. As @HedgeyeComm opined on Dec. 27, it would be possible for $NFLX to right its finances somewhat if it can pull back on its original content output and reposition itself as the licensed streaming platform of choice:  https://t.co/mDXeoqUSZ5

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 9/ If $NFLX continues to spend billions on new content with only limited (if any) financial return, it will find itself in peril. Netflix is already saddled with a massive long-term debt burden. As that comes due, fresh content production will become increasingly difficult.

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 8/ In other words, much of $NFLX's claimed content victory is likely down to gaming its own platform’s priorities. When a company has to resort to such gimmicks, it is usually a red flag for investors.  https://t.co/mDXeoqUSZ5

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 7/ That's a big shift in its own right, and liable to result in substantially different metrics. Distortion is all the more likely when one considers that $NFLX privileges its own content on its homepage, meaning that it often autoplays when users log on.  https://t.co/T5spSjJCV8

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 6/ According to a Wall Street Journal, $NFLX changed its methodology for determining what “watched” means in the context of views. It judged two minutes of streaming to count as a view. Yet this is very different from what Netflix has done in the past.  https://t.co/VcWuA2owhN

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 5/ On Dec. 30, $NFLX claimed that, of all films & series released on its platform in 2019, its own content won out as the most viewed. This might seem a vindication of the aggressive move into content. However, a look beneath the surface reveals something far less impressive.

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 4/ Of course, $NFLX's answer to this licensing problem has been to bet big on its own internally-produced content. But this is extremely expensive. Indeed, the company will likely spend $15B on content production in all of 2019. That's unsustainable.  https://t.co/mDXeoqUSZ5

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 3/ $NFLX is liable not only to face continued high licensing price escalation, but also to find that it will get substantially worse.  https://t.co/sZcs1esfS0

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 2/ During $NFLX's Q3 call, Reed Hastings was left briefly aghast when his chief content officer laid out the scale of escalation in 2019 alone. As @HedgeyeComm has pointed out, this escalation has emerged as the result of fierce and growing competition:  https://t.co/sdQ2vefVQ9

name: John Engle, Almington Capital Merchant Bankers
tweet: 1/ Licensing streaming content is wildly expensive, and is only getting more expensive as streaming platforms proliferate. Even Netflix’s top executives have been shocked at the pace of price escalation. $NFLX  https://t.co/mDXeoqUSZ5
